Cubic equation 


As for the  theory, to obtain an equation which is cubic in the resolvents, 
we need to consider more complicated transformations for ,  and . 
We thus add a - couple to the transformations () and (). 
There is more than one way to do so, because ,  and  do not commute: for 
the  variation we could put one of the two impurities on the left of the adjoint block 
and one on the right, or both on either side, while for the  variation we could use any of 
the combinations of two 's and one  between the two adjoint blocks. We will first 
rule out some of these possibilities, and then keep all of the remaining and calculate the anomaly 
equations for all of them: they will be just enough to obtain a cubic equation and evaluate the 
expectation values of all 4- operators.

First of all, we will not consider the adjoint transformations having one link(By link we mean an  or an  insertion either in the reparameterizations of the adjoint and bifundamental fields, or in the trace operators.)  on 
the left and one on the right. This is obvious since to build such a variation the adjoint 
field we insert must be different from the adjoint field we are varying 
(e.g. ), thus the quantum contribution 
to the anomaly (the commutator part in the first of ()) vanishes, and only the 
classical part contributes, which is telling us nothing more about the low energy dynamics of 
the theory, than the classical equations of motion do. The choices with both  and  on 
the left, or both of them on the right are actually equivalent because of the cyclicity of the trace (). 
Thus we are left with only two possible variations for the adjoint fields, which correspond to the two 
orderings of the pair  on the right of the adjoint block.

The variations we consider are then
