Outlook of the general procedure 



Based on the experience we gained in writing the general form of the quadratic and cubic equations for the resolvents, in this section we give some hints on how to write all the equations up to the  grade for a  quiver theory, even though we won't be able to evaluate them explicitly.

First of all we want to give a rule that tells us which are the relevant reparameterizations we have to use.

It is a general feature of alternating perturbations, that is perturbations whose chain is an alternating array of 's and 's, to give the same Ward identities. In fact, let us consider a generic degree  alternating chain
 
&X_k,k+1 =X(X X)^p1 

&X _k+1,k =1 X (XX )^p
then it is easy to show that both variations lead to the same Ward identity
 
-&1(X X)^p+1 +(XX )^p+1 =
&=-_m=0 ^p (XX )^m1(X X)^p-m 
One of these variations is then redundant, and must be neglected.

Let us now define a conjugation relation among  and 
 transformations: we say that a  and a  variations 
are conjugated if the - chain of either can be obtained from the 
other's by inverting it and taking the "complex conjugate" (e.g. ()
 and () are conjugated in this sense). A  variation will contain as many  factors as   are present in the  conjugated variation, and, moreover, they are in specular positions. Thus the right hand side of the Ward identities () generated by this pair will contain the same number of elements, and the number of links in each of the two factors of each element will be equal.

There is even more to this: the right hand side of the two Ward identities will be equal. In fact let us consider an  field in the  variation, on both sides of it there will be an equal number of  and  fields (even though the number of pairs on one side will in general be different from the number on the other side), because we are left with two fields in the adjoint one of  and the other of . Let us now consider its image  through the conjugation operation. The same will be true for this field also, with representations exchanged. Now, because of the way we have defined conjugation, the subarray on the left of  will be equal to the subarray on the right of  and viceversa. Let us make an example: we consider a general variation  and its conjugated partner and indicate with a hat the two conjugated links
 
&X_k,k+1 =X_k,k+1 XX X X _k,k+1 XX 1 z-_(k+1)  

&X _k+1,k =1 XX X  _k+1,k XXX X _k+1,k 1 z-_(k)  
Thus taking the difference of the equations we obtain from two conjugated variations, gives an identity for four-link operators.

Unfortunately, we are not able to give an a priori  prescription which tells us which conjugated pairs will give the same four-link identity. This will have to be checked case by case.

Once all variations and Ward identities have been written, it is not hard to write a  degree equation involving only the resolvents. Let us suppose we have written the  degree equation, and have evaluated the expectation values of all operators with  pairs of bifundamentals. Then we only have to sum all reparameterizations for the adjoint fields and alternating transformations for  containing  couples -, use the -link identities we have obtained from conjugated pairs, and make use of lower-degree equations. What we obtain is the -degree equation for the resolvents of a  () quiver theory.




